@section overview Overview

<b>%LT Libraries</b><br>
All software that runs on %LT, whether OS components or product specific
software, is packaged and delivered in <i>%LT Libraries</i> which are dynamically
loadable libraries which each export 1 and only 1 <i>library root interface</i> which is a
C++ pure virtual class that acts as a factory for other objects exported from
the library.

The foundational library of the %LT Operating system is the %LTCore library which
is used to %Open() additional libraries.  The handle to the %LTCore library is
always available with a call to the static function @c LT_GetCore().

<b>Self Containment and Platform Independence</b><br>
%LT as an operating system is _self-contained_.  This means that it does not
have any external dependencies outside of itself.
<br>
<br>
The purpose of self-containment is to:
<ul style="margin-top: -1em">
    <li>enable %LT to be fully <b>platform-independent</b>, meaning it may be brought up on
         other systems with a straight recompile, using <b>zero</b> conditional compilation \#ifdefs.</li>
    <li> enable %LT to be deterministically <b>maximally compatible</b> with severely
         constrained secure IoT environments
         such as the Microsoft IoT Azure Sphere Operating System/Kernel where only proprietary
         Azure Sphere APIs are accessible.</li></ul>

The property of self-containment is enacted via adherence to these constraints:
<ul style="margin-top: -1em">
<li>%LT Library public API files may only \#include:<ol>
    <li>other header files that are part of its own Library Public API</li>
    <li>public API header files from any other %LT library</li></ol></li>
<li>%LT Library implementation files may only \#include:<ol>
    <li>header files internal to its own implementation</li>
    <li>header files of its own public API</li>
    <li>public API header files from any other %LT library</li></ol></li></ul>

Any library that follows these rules is, by %LT's definition, _platform independent_ and
will operate deterministically on all platforms with a simple recompile.

As a concrete and somewhat non-obvious example of self-containment, %LT Libraries <b>may not \#include standard library header files</b> such as <stdio.h> nor operating system header files such as <sys/socket.h>.  %LTCore abstracts common stdio functions and the %LTNetwork library provides access to sockets.

<b>Device Drivers and Third Party Libraries</b>

<ul style="margin-top: -1em">
    <li>Driver libraries, by necessity, must access platform specfic functionality.
        While their interfaces are platform independent and must remain so, their implementations
        are permitted to \#include device specific functionality, but only by necessity
        as required.</li>
    <li>Third-party library use is strongly discouraged. Any incorporation of a third-party
        library must be pre-approved by the %LT Architecture Committee.  %Third-party libraries
        are incorporated as platform independent %LT libraries (like Device libraries) that thunk
        into platform dependent third party %LT Driver libraries.  It is these %LT Driver Libraries
        that access the third party library api directly.  In this manner dependency creep is
        isolated when incorporating third-party libraries.  Roku strives to eschew third party
        library support in %LT in favor of clean room implementations.
    <li>The %LTCore library, which abstracts the OS kernel, has multiple implementations which,
        by design, \#include platform specific functionality; in effect, %LTCore exists to enable
        self-containment.</li>>
    <li><b>No implementation of <i>any</i> %LT library</b> shall \#include any header file
        that is not part of the collection of public %LT Library API header files, expect for
        LTDriver libraries.</li>
</ul>


@section starting Getting Started

<ul><li>class LT illustrates how to obtain the %LTCore library interface.</li>
<li>class LTCore is the library root interface of the %LTCore library and is the starting point for
creating operating system objects.</li></ul>


@class LT LT.h <lt/LT.h>
@brief interface for initialization and termination of the %LT Operating System, and for access to the LTCore library

<a href="#themeat"><b>Skip the description</b></a>

The %LT Operating System is started with a call to LT::Run() which is typically only called once in a device that runs a real-time operating system.  %Run() initializes the LTCore library and makes %LT::GetCore() available globally.

LT::Terminate() may be called to terminate the LT Operating System session.  The session is terminated by sending a terminate message to all running threads and waiting until all threads have terminated..  This is typically never performed when running on a device with a real-time operating system as they are typically designed to never exit.

LT::GetCore() can be called from any library to return a pointer
to the LTCore instance, allowing access to LTCore services.

@see LTCore

*/
